Three agents — a yard operator who dispatches the inbound and outbound robotic trucks, a logistics planner who holds the dynamic yard map, and a crane operator who executes one physical crane move per tool call — coordinate over a shared link channel to place one incoming container into its correct slot each round across {{ round_count }} rounds. Customs inspectors are waiting at the target slot: the container must reach that slot within a fixed {{ time_budget_seconds }}-second inspection window or the inspection is missed and the round fails. Every character sent on the link channel costs one simulated second against that window.

The yard operator alone sees the incoming container's ID. The logistics planner alone sees the round's yard map: which crane stations are active, the two transfer pads at each station, which stacks each station can reach, the current four-stack layout, and the shift manifest of scheduled inbound containers paired with their target slots. The planner does not know which scheduled container is on this round's inbound truck and must wait for the yard operator to report it before constructing any plan. The crane operator sees only their crane and the link channel; they cannot solve a round on their own. Some rounds need a buried-slot reshuffle: one blocker container must be lifted onto a separate outbound truck (which leaves loaded) before the inbound truck's container can be placed.

Round success requires all of: every expected truck arrives at the correct station and pad carrying the correct container (the inbound truck always; the outbound truck whenever the target slot is already occupied, arriving empty); every expected crane move is executed in the right order by the right container, with each source currently accessible and each destination currently free; and the inspection window is not exhausted.
